Using MATLAB deep learning toolbox

At this moment, I didn't work out a better solution to perfectly match what Michael had written in Python. Instead, I was going to use the Deep Learning Toolbox directly provided in MATLAB. This is kind of an advanced way to construct neural network models with the disadvantage of hiding everything in the packed black box. It is however in general easier to understand the model construction. But I still strongly suggest you go through Michael's Python program in order to digest the details of each layer (or go through MATLAB source codes in order to understand details--I personally have done this long time ago many times--It may appears to be messy now at the very initial but eventually you'll get into it).
Before going to a DL model, let's first try out a shallow model, the three-layer (including an input and an output layer) fully-connected model.
clc; close; clear;
MATLAB has two ways to manage source data--a datastore or a variable loaded in memory. Datastore makes it possible to handle millions of input images which are not possible to be imported to memory at the same time. MATLAB will automate this by consitently interacting with the place where data are saved. To use the datastore mechanism, I have to save all MNIST data to local. I've saved all images to local folders "MNIST_train" and "MNIST_test". In each folder, I have 10 different folders named with the label of these images. If you want to do so, you can find in this repo the program I used to do the saving "prepareData2Local".
I added numTrainingFiles and numTestFiles to speed up. You can change it to use the full dataset.

ind_valid = randperm(size(imgDataTrain, 4), 10000);
ind_train = setxor(1:size(imgDataTrain, 4), ind_valid);
imgDataTrain_ = imgDataTrain(:, :, :, ind_train);
labelsTrain_ = labelsTrain(ind_train);
imgDataValid = imgDataTrain(:, :, :, ind_valid);
labelsValid = labelsTrain(ind_valid);
The following is the model construction.
Note that for some reason MATLAB never has provided a sigmoidLayer while the default classificationLayer need to be preceded with a softmax layer. I've custmozed a sigmoidLayer which is in this repo too. I've also customized a crossEntropyClassificationLayer. However, at this moment it still doesn't work as even with the crossEntropyClassificationLayer, I've prompted the same error saying that a softmaxLayer is required. Anyway the crossEntropyClassificationLayer was customized from a template MATLAB provided which may lead to this messy. I've temporarily given this up and will come back at some point if I've worked out a solution.
The other point that worths noting is that layers are highly separated based on MATLAB's DL structure. In fullyConnectedLayer, you can consider it as only doing the weighted sum while the activation is done in the following sigmoidLayer (one input and one output). The loss is calculated in the classificationLayer.
Layer = [imageInputLayer([28, 28, 1])
fullyConnectedLayer(100, 'WeightsInitializer', "he", 'BiasInitializer', "narrow-normal")
sigmoidLayer
fullyConnectedLayer(10, 'WeightsInitializer', "he", 'BiasInitializer', "narrow-normal")
softmaxLayer
classificationLayer
];
Train options
options = trainingOptions('sgdm', 'MaxEpochs', 30, ...
'Shuffle', 'every-epoch', "MiniBatchSize", 200, ...
"ValidationData", {imgDataValid(:, :, :, :), labelsValid(:)}, ...
'ValidationFrequency', 100, ...
"InitialLearnRate", 0.1, ...
"LearnRateSchedule", "piecewise", ...
"LearnRateDropPeriod", 500, ...
'LearnRateDropFactor', 0.2, ...
'Momentum', 0, ...
"L2Regularization", 0.001, ...
"Plots", 'training-progress', ...
'Verbose', 0);
net = trainNetwork(imgDataTrain_(:, :, :, :), labelsTrain_(:), Layer, options);
Okay 94.4% accuray is what I got so far. Not as encouraging as previous tests that were done by scripts. The reason I'm saying this is that remember we've already reached 94% using the first model (with 30 hidden neurons, large weight initiation and without regularization). But here I've used 100 hidden neurons and have set up some weight initializer (essentially option "he" is the same as the default weight initiation in gnnet.m) and with L2 regularization. I've also let learning rate drop per 500 iterations (i.e., 2 epochs since I've set miniBatchSize as 200).
You may get a better result if you further tune these parameters.
However, what is even less encouraging is that I've never reached to even 80% if I change the sigmoidLayer to softmaxLayer in the first fullyConnectedLayer. Not quite sure why this is this case but am just guessing that softmax activation seems not quite good for such a shallow network structure. Anyway at this moment I can't switch the second softmaxLayer to sigmoidLayer as MATLAB will be complaining about this. Let's first stop here and move forward to a deeper model.
